			<p><a href="http://www.plosmedicine.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.0020298" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-comment','http://www.plosmedicine.org']);" rel="nofollow">http://www.plosmedicine.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.0020298</a><br />
<a href="http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0140673607603122?via=sd&#038;cc=y" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-comment','http://linkinghub.elsevier.com']);" rel="nofollow">http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0140673607603122?via=sd&#038;cc=y</a></p>
<p>Some things are more important than respecting babies bodies. I have heard that circumcision is quite a horrid procedure to go through as an adult, and circumcising your son makes him 60% less likely to contract HIV. It might not be ideal to make changes to a baby&#8217;s body before he is old enough to decide for himself, but life is not perfect, and compromises have to be made. By circumcising your son you are not only protecting him, but everyone else he may have sex with or rape in the future. </p>
<p>Maybe the US has a higher incidence of HIV because people don&#8217;t use condoms? There are too many other variables to consider, that is why scientists do controlled studies.  I challenge you to find a study that backs up your claims.</p>
