		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>The section: <b>1. Education about “good touch/bad touch” remains crucial</b> does not come across as gender neutral and it culminating with it&#8217;s <i>This isn’t “boys being boys”, this is harassment, and sometimes assault.</i> line cements that impression.</p>
<p>Take this a as a constructive criticism of what you seemed to have overlooked in what otherwise was a pretty good article.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ll echo part from a great <a href="http://goodmenproject.com/good-feed-blog/hesaidop-ed-this-is-not-how-you-support-mens-issues/comment-page-1/#comment-475198"  rel="nofollow">comment</a><a> by Greg Allen:</p>
<blockquote><p>
Boys are not taught about consent properly to begin with. Such right to consent that they do have is presented as always secondary to that of the other party. It’s an obligation rather than a right for them. How can they understand consent if it isn’t something they possess themselves?
</p></blockquote>
<p>as a reason why I think  it&#8217;s very important to keep lessons on consent gender neutral. As Greg Allen point out in that comment &#8211; a not insignificant number of boys have been a victim of CSA and women are also among the perpetrators and having a &#8220;men can stop rape&#8221; single focus on teaching consent is basically telling them that their abuser was not responsible for her actions.</a></p>
